'''Bernard G. Weiss''' (10 August 1933–8 February 2018) was a [[professor]] of [[linguistics|languages]] and [[literature]] at the [[University of Utah]].<ref>[http://content.lib.utah.edu/cdm/ref/collection/upcat/id/1228 The Search for God's Law]</ref><ref>[http://www.languages.utah.edu/?module=facultyDetails&personId=59&orgId=299 Bernard Weiss]</ref> He has an extensive publication record and is recognized as one of the foremost scholars in [[Islamic law]], [[Islamic theology]], [[Islamic philosophy]], [[Islamic political thought]], [[Arab history]] and Muslim discussions of [[linguistics]] and the [[origin of language]].<ref>[http://menadoc.bibliothek.uni-halle.de/download/pdf/96002?name=Medieval%20Muslim%20Discussions%20of%20the%20Origin%20of%20Language Medieval Muslim Discussions of the Origin of Language]</ref><ref>[http://law.wustl.edu/wugslr/issues/volume1/p553el%20fadl.pdf Soul Searching and the Spirit of Shari'ah: A Review of Bernard Weiss' The Spirit of Islamic Law], [[Khaled Abou El Fadl]], Washington University Global Studies Law Review, vol. 1, nos. 1 and 2, Winter/Summer 2002, pp.553-72</ref>
==Life== Weiss received his PhD from [[Princeton University]] in 1966.<ref>[http://www.humis.utah.edu/humis/docs/organization_299_1251999179.pdf Languages and Literature Newsletter]</ref>
==Bibliography== * ''Studies in Islamic Law and Society'' * ''Religion and Law: Biblical-judaic and Islamic Perspectives'' * ''Studies in Islamic Legal Theory'' * ''A Survey of Arab History'', 1988 * ''The Spirit of Islamic Law'', Athens, Georgia: University of Georgia Press, 1998. * (ed. with [[Peri Bearman]] and [[Wolfhart Heinrichs]]) ''The Law Applied: Contextualizing the Islamic Shari`a'', London and New York: I.B. Tauris, 2008. * ''The Search for God's Law: Islamic Jurisprudence in the Writings of Sayf al-Din al-Amidi'', 2010 * ''Language in Orthodox Muslim Thought: A Study of "Wad Al-lughah" and Its Development''
