'''John Stearne''' (c. 1610–1670)<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l-09bxmMZPIC&printsec=frontcover&hl=hu&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Discovery of Witches and Witchcraft: The Writings of the Witchfinders|first1=S.F|last=Davies|publisher=Puckrel|year=2007}}</ref> was an associate of self-styled "Witchfinder General" [[Matthew Hopkins]], a witch-hunter active during the [[English Civil War]].<ref>A detailed account of the duo's activities can be found in Malcolm Gaskill's ''Witchfinders: A Seventeenth Century English Tragedy'' (Harvard, 2005). The duo's activities were portrayed unreliably, but entertainingly, in the 1968 cult classic [[Witchfinder General (film)|''Witchfinder-General'']] (U.S. title: ''The Conqueror Worm'').</ref> Stearne was known at various times as the witch-hunter,<ref>{{cite web | last = St Edmundsbury | first = Borough Council | title = Reformation and Civil War 1539-1699 | url=http://www.stedmundsbury.gov.uk/sebc/visit/1539-1699.cfm | accessdate = 2007-12-15 }}</ref><ref>[[#Witchcraft|Notestein 1911]]: p166</ref> and "witch pricker".<ref>[[#Witchcraft|Notestein 1911]]: p248</ref> Raised in [[Long Melford]], Suffolk<ref>https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=B5Yl4DiTo9MC&pg=PA84&lpg=PA84&dq=john+stearne+long+melford&source=bl&ots=-6dL9_hrk6&sig=0r_QISNHeIW__mvnS004CQJuy-o&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwilxdTP3aPeAhWF2KQKHZA0Ag8Q6AEwCHoECAYQAQ#v=onepage&q=john%20stearne%20long%20melford&f=false</ref>, Stearne later became a land owner at [[Lawshall]] near [[Bury St Edmunds]]<ref>[[#Witchfinders|Gaskill 2005]]: p13</ref>. He met Hopkins, who was 10 years' his junior, in [[Manningtree]] and appointed him as his assistant. As a result of Stearne's accusations, a trial was held in [[Chelmsford]] in July 1645 for 29 people accused of witchcraft and sorcery.<ref name="page123">[[#Witchfinders|Gaskill 2005]]: p123</ref> Of these four had died in prison prior to the trial<ref name="page123"/> and 15 or 16<ref>[[#Witchcraft|Notestein 1911]]: p173; 403</ref> were subsequently hanged. Nine who had been convicted of [[Evocation|conjuring]] spirits were reprieved.<ref>[[#Witchfinders|Gaskill 2005]]: p129</ref>
Within a year of the death of Matthew Hopkins, John Stearne retired to his farm and wrote ''A Confirmation and Discovery of Witchcraft''.
