[[File:Lulu M Hefner portrait.jpg|thumb|Lulu M. Hefner]]
'''Lulu M. Hefner''' (or Heffner, b. August 9, 1874 and d. July 19, 1954) was a [[Cherokee people|Cherokee]] businessperson from [[Nowata, Oklahoma]]. She is known as the first woman to drill a producing [[oil well]] on her own property, and the first female [[Oil in Oklahoma|oil operator in Oklahoma]].<ref name=starr1921 /> As of 1821, Hefner had drilled 28 successful wells, managed a motion picture theater, and owned the largest garage in the state.<ref>{{cite book|title=Independent Woman|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zBFAAQAAMAAJ&pg=PT120|year=1921|publisher=National Federation of Business and Professional Women's Clubs|page=120}}</ref> She was active in the civic and social affairs of the Nowata community. Her initial business in Nowata was the town's first [[millinery]] store.
Lula May, the daughter of James Marion and Annie Henrietta (Prather) Tittle, was born August 9, 1874, and educated at [[Vinita, Oklahoma]] and the [[Cherokee Female Seminary]]. She married John Emory Heffner at [[Lenapah, Oklahoma]] on December 29, 1892. They had four children: Roy Emory, born March 13, 1903, Edith Lena, born December 18, 1905; Helen K., born October 2, 1905 and Ruby L., born January 20, 1907.<ref name=starr1921>{{Cite book | publisher = The Warden Company | last = Starr | first = Emmett | title = History of the Cherokee Indians and their legends and folk lore | location = Oklahoma City | accessdate = 2014-09-02 | date = 1921 | url = https://archive.org/stream/historyofcheroke00lcstar#page/494/mode/2up }}</ref>
