[[General]] '''Michel Micombero''' (August 26, 1940 – July 16, 1983) was a [[Burundi]]an politician and soldier who ruled the country as its first [[List of Presidents of Burundi|president]] and ''de facto'' [[dictator]] for the decade between 1966 and 1976. He was a member of the [[Tutsi|Tutsi ethnic group]].

Beginning his career as an officer in the [[Military of Burundi|Burundian army]], Micombero studied in [[Belgium]] and rose to prominence for his role in helping to foil an attempted [[1965 Burundian coup d'état attempt|coup d'état in October 1965]] where [[Hutu|ethnic Hutu]] soldiers attempted to overthrow the [[Kingdom of Burundi|country's (Tutsi) monarchy]]. After becoming prime minister in July 1966, Micombero led two further coup d'états against the monarchy, which he perceived as too moderate, and installed himself as president in November 1966. 

As President, Micombero ruled Burundi as a [[military dictator]]. He led a [[one-party state]] which centralised the country's institutions and adopted a neutral stance in the [[Cold War]]. Dissent was repressed and, in 1972, an attempt to challenge Micombero's power led to [[Burundian genocides|a genocide]] against the Hutu population in which around 100,000 people, mainly Hutus, were killed. His regime finally collapsed in 1976 when he was ousted in [[1976 Burundian coup d'état|a coup d'état]] by [[Jean-Baptiste Bagaza]]. Micombero went into exile in [[Somali Democratic Republic|Somalia]] where he died in 1983.

==Biography==
===Origins and early political career===
Micombero was born in [[Rutovu]], [[Bururi Province]] in [[Ruanda-Urundi|Belgian-ruled Ruanda-Urundi]] on 26 August 1940. His parents were peasants from the [[Hema people]], part of the [[Tutsi]] ethnic group.{{sfn|African Biography|2008}} Micombero studied at [[Catholicism|Catholic]] mission schools in [[Burundi]] and, in 1960, joined the [[Military of Burundi|Burundian military]] which was being formed ahead of planned independence in 1962.{{sfn|African Biography|2008}} As part of his training, he was sent to study at the [[Royal Military Academy (Belgium)|Royal Military Academy]] in [[Brussels]], [[Belgium]] to train as an officer.{{sfn|African Biography|2008}} At the time of the independence of the [[Kingdom of Burundi]] in July 1962, he held the rank of [[captain]].{{sfn|African Biography|2008}}

In early post-independence Burundi, the Tutsi-dominated monarchy of [[Mwambutsa IV]] attempted to balance the interests of Tutsi with those of the Hutu majority. In 1963, Micombero joined the ruling [[Union for National Progress]] (UPRONA) party which, though dominated by Tutsi, also tried to attract Hutu members.{{sfn|African Biography|2008}} In June, Micombero was named [[State Secretary for Defense]], making him head of the military at the age of 23.{{sfn|African Biography|2008}} In October 1965, a group of ethnic Hutus [[1965 Burundian coup d'état attempt|attempted to overthrow the Burundian monarchy]]. Their attempt, though unsuccessful, led to Mwambutsa IV fleeing into exile. Micombero led the repression against the coup's perpetrators.{{sfn|African Biography|2008}} In July 1966, a [[July 1966 Burundian coup d'état|second coup d'état]] brought the king's son, [[Ntare V]], to power and suspended the national constitution. However, when Ntare was on a [[state visit]] to the [[Republic of the Congo (Léopoldville)|neighbouring Republic of the Congo]] in November 1966, a [[November 1966 Burundian coup d'état|third coup d'état]] abolished the monarchy and a [[republic]] was proclaimed on 28 November.{{sfn|African Biography|2008}} As a [[colonel]], Micombero took power as the country's first [[President of Burundi|President]] in December 1966.{{sfn|African Biography|2008}}

===Dictatorship===
[[File:Burundi in its region.svg|thumb|Location of [[Burundi]] in [[Central Africa]] ]]
As President of Burundi, Micombero ruled through UPRONA as a [[one-party state]]. His ideology of "democratic centralism" brought all the country's institutions and media under the regime's control.{{sfn|African Biography|2008}} His regime combined ideas from [[Ujamaa|the socialist ideology]] of [[Tanzania]] with other doctrines from [[Mobutu Sese Seko|Joseph-Désiré Mobutu]]'s regime in the Congo.{{sfn|African Biography|2008}} As a [[Cold War]] leader, he was able to play off both Communist and Western powers against one another.{{sfn|African Biography|2008}}

Micombero became increasingly paranoid after suffering an injury in a road accident in 1967.{{sfn|African Biography|2008}} He was widely believed to be an [[alcoholic]]. Various plots against the regime were discovered and unrest remained.{{sfn|African Biography|2008}} His base of support became increasingly restricted to Tutsi in the northern and central regions of Burundi.{{sfn|African Biography|2008}}

In April 1972, a major rebellion broke out among the Hutu in the south at the encouragement of the Tanzanian regime.{{sfn|African Biography|2008}} In subsequent ethnic violence, as many as 1,000 Tutsi were killed. The reaction of the Micombero regime was to launch [[Burundian genocides|a genocidal campaign]] against the Hutu in the region in which around 100,000 people are thought to have been killed. The deposed king Ntare, said to have led the rebellion, was murdered.{{sfn|African Biography|2008}} In 1973, after further violence, the Congolese Mobutu regime had to intervene to prevent Tanzanian invasion.{{sfn|African Biography|2008}} Following the end of the crisis, Micombero introduced a new [[constitution]] allowing him to run for a further seven-year term. He also laid the foundation for the [[Economic Community of the Great Lakes Countries]] the same year, along with the governments of [[Rwanda]] and Congo.{{sfn|African Biography|2008}} 

In November 1976, opponents of Micombero's regime, led by Colonel [[Jean-Baptiste Bagaza]], led a [[1976 Burundian coup d'état|successful coup d'état]]. Micombero himself was arrested and a second republic was declared under the dictatorship of Bagaza which would last until 1987.{{sfn|African Biography|2008}}

===Exile and death===
Micombero was exiled from Burundi in 1977.{{sfn|African Biography|2008}} He took up residence in [[Somali Democratic Republic|Somalia]], then ruled by dictator [[Siad Barre]] who was a close friend. He gained a degree in economics from the [[University of Somalia]] in 1982.{{sfn|The New York Times|1983}} He died of a heart attack in 1983.{{sfn|The New York Times|1983}}

