'''Nikolai Vasilyevich Rumyantsev''' ({{lang-ru|Николай Васильевич Румянцев}}, 1892–1956) was a [[Soviet]] author of several polemics on the [[history of Christianity]]. He was also a member of the Soviet circle "[[Atheist (magazine)|Atheist]]" and the [[League of Militant Atheists]].<ref name="Rumyantsev">{{cite web | url =http://ateism.academic.ru/23690/%D0%A0%D0%A3%D0%9C%D0%AF%D0%9D%D0%A6%D0%95%D0%92_%D0%9D%D0%B8%D0%BA%D0%BE%D0%BB%D0%B0%D0%B9_%D0%92%D0%B0%D1%81%D0%B8%D0%BB%D1%8C%D0%B5%D0%B2%D0%B8%D1%87|title=Румянцев Николай Васильевич|work=Атеистический словарь| date=1986|publisher=Политиздат|editor=М. П. Новиков| language=Russian|accessdate =12 June 2015}}</ref> In the 1920s Rumyantsev was one of the leading proponents of the so-called mythological school in the Soviet academia.<ref name="Thrower">{{cite book | author=James Thrower| title =Marxist-Leninist 'Scientific Atheism' and the Study of Religion and Atheism in the USSR| publisher =Walter de Gruyter| year =1983| page =427| isbn =3110838583}}</ref> He authored such publications, as "The Pre-Christian Christ" ({{lang-ru|"Дохристианский Христос"}}, 1926), "The Pagan Christs – the Ancient Precursors of Christianity" ({{lang-ru|"Языческие христы: Античные предшественники христианства"}},  1929), "The Apocalypse – The Revelation of John" ({{lang-ru|"Апокалипсис - откровение Иоанна, его происхождение и классовая роль"}},  1934) and "Orthodox Holidays, Their Origin and Class Essence" (1936).<ref name="Rumyantsev"/> "The Apocalypse – The Revelation of John" was published under the influence of [[Abram Ranovich]].<ref name="Thrower"/> In that publication Rumyantsev, while not explicitly retracting his earlier opinions, offered a study of [[early Christianity]] which stressed not its derivation from supposed ancient mythology, but its intrinsic relation to revolutionary, messianic elements in contemporary [[Judaism]].<ref name="Thrower"/>

