{{Nihongo|'''Yōhei Kōno''' |河野 洋平|Kōno Yōhei|extra=born 15 January 1937 in [[Hiratsuka, Kanagawa]]}} is a Japanese politician and a former President of the [[Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)|Liberal Democratic Party]]. He served as Speaker of the [[House of Representatives of Japan|House of Representatives]] from November 2003 until August 2009, when the LDP lost its majority in the [[Japanese general election, 2009|2009 election]]. Kōno served as speaker for the longest length since the set up of House of Representatives in 1890.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kono's tenure longest as speaker|url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20081120a9.html|accessdate=22 November 2008|work=The Japan Times |date=20 November 2008}}</ref>
He was the president of the [[Japan Association of Athletics Federations]] from 1999 to 2013.<ref>[http://www.jaaf.or.jp/rikuren/about.html {{Nihongo||日本陸連歴代会長・理事長・専務理事|The Successive President and Vice-President and Senior-Managing-Director of JAAF}}] {{ja icon}} [[Japan Association of Athletics Federations]]. Retrieved 13 June 2012.</ref>

== History ==
Kōno is the eldest son of [[Ichirō Kōno]], a former minister dealing with the [[1964 Summer Olympics|Tokyo Olympic Games]].  [[Kenzō Kōno]], the chairman of the [[House of Councillors]] is his younger uncle.

After graduating from [[Waseda University]], Kōno worked with the [[Marubeni]] company. In 1967, Kono's political career began due to the death of his father.

== Political career ==
[[File:Murayama Government 19950808.jpg|thumb|left|with members of [[Murayama Cabinet|Murayama Reshuffled Cabinet]] (at the [[Prime Minister's Official Residence]] on August 8, 1995)]]
He was Deputy Prime Minister from 1994 to 1995. He was Minister of Foreign Affairs under Prime Minister [[Tomiichi Murayama]] and Murayama's successor [[Yoshirō Mori]]. He is a member of the [[Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)|Liberal Democratic Party]] (LDP). He was once President of the LDP from 1993 to 1995, and to date is the only LDP leader except for [[Sadakazu Tanigaki]] to have never served as [[Prime Minister of Japan]]. As he is one of the pro-Chinese members of the LDP, he came under pressure domestically in the spring of 2005 when anti-Japanese movements in China became intense.

Kōno is well known as a controversial figure within the ''[[comfort women]]'' debate, for the [[Kono Statement of 1993|official statement he made in 1993]], when he was Chief Cabinet Secretary. In his statement, made after historian [[Yoshiaki Yoshimi]] announced he had discovered in the Defense Agency library in Tokyo documentary evidence that the [[Imperial Japanese Army]] established and ran "comfort stations", he essentially admitted that the Japanese Imperial Army had been involved, directly and indirectly, in the establishment of ''comfort facilities'', and that coercion had been used in the recruitment and retention of the women. His subsequent call for historical research and education aimed at remembering the issue became the basis for addressing the subject of forced prostitution in school history textbooks.

